SM121 (DGX Spark GB10) shared memory fix for cutlass_moe_fp4 / nvfp4_blockwise_moe

Problem:
  Both SM120 (RTX 5090, RTX PRO 6000 Blackwell) and SM121 (DGX Spark GB10)
  provide only 99 KiB (101376 bytes) of shared memory per thread block.
  The 228 KiB figure that's often cited for "Blackwell" belongs to SM100
  (B200), not SM12x — per CUTLASS maintainer @depaulmillz in
  NVIDIA/cutlass#3144.

  CUTLASS's run_fp4_blockwise_scaled_group_mm_sm120() path in
  nvfp4_blockwise_moe.cuh uses the Pingpong ptr-array schedule, which
  together with StageCountAutoCarveout requests exactly 102400 bytes
  (100 KiB) of mainloop SMEM — just 1 KiB over the 99 KiB device
  budget. The CUDA runtime then fails with a device-side assert at
  line 78 whenever the triton or cutlass MoE runner dispatches to
  cutlass_moe_fp4 for NVFP4 weights.

  Confirmed trigger on DGX Spark: any NVFP4 model (Qwen3-235B-A22B-NVFP4,
  GLM-4.7-NVFP4, Qwen3.5-397B-A17B-NVFP4, etc.) run with
  moe_runner_backend=triton or =cutlass under SGLang v0.5.10.

Fix:
  Switch the ptr-array kernel schedule from
    KernelPtrArrayTmaWarpSpecializedPingpong
  to
    KernelPtrArrayTmaWarpSpecializedCooperative.

  Both 2-math-warp-group schedules, but with fundamentally different
  SMEM footprints:

  - Pingpong runs the two math warp groups on DIFFERENT output tiles
    concurrently; each group needs its own mainloop+epilogue buffers,
    so mainloop SMEM is effectively doubled. That duplication is what
    pushes the allocation from ~99 KiB → 100 KiB on SM120/121.

  - Cooperative runs both math warp groups on the SAME output tile
    (one operates on the "upper half" of the M dimension, the other
    on the "lower half"); they SHARE the mainloop buffers. One
    producer warp still handles TMA loads. Net mainloop SMEM is
    comparable to a single-group warp-specialized kernel, comfortably
    under the 99 KiB budget.

  The Sm120 block-scaled CollectiveBuilder at
  cutlass/gemm/collective/builders/sm120_blockscaled_mma_builder.inl:72
  explicitly accepts BOTH KernelPtrArrayTmaWarpSpecializedPingpong and
  KernelPtrArrayTmaWarpSpecializedCooperative as valid tags for
  ArchTag=Sm120 + OpClassBlockScaledTensorOp, so Cooperative is a
  drop-in replacement — no other template parameter needs to change.

  StageCountAutoCarveout is kept unchanged. With Cooperative's lower
  mainloop footprint, the automatic stage count calculation picks a
  valid pipelining depth from the remaining SMEM budget without any
  manual override. Earlier attempts to force StageCount<1> or
  StageCount<2> under Pingpong failed CUTLASS SFINAE because the
  schedule tag used (KernelPtrArrayTmaWarpSpecialized without the
  Pingpong/Cooperative suffix) does not exist in CUTLASS — only the
  two suffixed variants are defined. The correct fix is the schedule
  swap, not a stage-count override.

  The ThreadBlockShape<_128, _128, _128> is unchanged — TMA descriptor
  validation allows schedule changes but rejects M/N reduction.

  This follows the same general approach TensorRT-LLM merged in PR #12141
  (2026-03-18) for the analogous fp4_gemm_template.h path on SM121, though
  their fix operates on a different layer of the CUTLASS stack.

Refs:
  - https://github.com/NVIDIA/cutlass/issues/3144
      Root cause. Contains the verbatim SMEM numbers above
      (228 KiB SM100 vs 99 KiB SM120/121, 102400/101376 failure case).
  - https://github.com/NVIDIA/TensorRT-LLM/pull/12141
      Reference fix from NVIDIA maintainers for the TRT-LLM FP4 GEMM path.
  - https://github.com/sgl-project/sglang/pull/20012
      JIT migration: the target file moved from sgl-kernel/csrc/moe/
      to python/sglang/jit_kernel/csrc/moe/.

Upstream source: sgl-project/sglang tag v0.5.10

--- a/python/sglang/jit_kernel/csrc/moe/nvfp4_blockwise_moe.cuh
+++ b/python/sglang/jit_kernel/csrc/moe/nvfp4_blockwise_moe.cuh
@@ -329,7 +329,11 @@
       ClusterShape,
       cutlass::gemm::collective::StageCountAutoCarveout<static_cast<int>(
           sizeof(typename CollectiveEpilogue::SharedStorage))>,
-      cutlass::gemm::KernelPtrArrayTmaWarpSpecializedPingpong>::CollectiveOp;
+      // SM120/121 have 99 KiB SMEM/block — not 228 KiB like SM100 (see
+      // CUTLASS#3144). Pingpong duplicates mainloop buffers across its
+      // two persistent math warp groups → 1 KiB over budget. Cooperative
+      // lets both groups share buffers on the same tile → fits.
+      cutlass::gemm::KernelPtrArrayTmaWarpSpecializedCooperative>::CollectiveOp;
 
   using GemmKernel = cutlass::gemm::kernel::GemmUniversal<ProblemShape, CollectiveMainloop, CollectiveEpilogue>;
 
